We‚Äôve been doing so many different things lately, but A has really loved BAKING! One of his favorite books right now is ‚ÄúStir, Crack, Whisk, Bake‚Äù so when I asked him if he wanted to bake some cupcakes, he was ready! üßëüèΩ‚Äçüç≥ A has been picking up more and more skills around the kitchen (and around the house) and he was ready to take on some additional responsibilities. Swipe üëâüèª to see our little chef in action! I made sure to have all of our materials and ingredients already out before we started because there were plenty of other moments where he would have to be patient and wait (something we‚Äôre working on right now). 

This activity had many learning opportunities for A!

üßÅ Math and Literacy: From measuring out the different ingredients to counting out how many cupcake liners we would need, A was able to learn and strengthen his math vocabulary and skills. Talking about stirring the batter, pouring the water, mixing the egg replacer, baking the cupcakes, and so much more helped him understand what was happening and what to expect next. 

üßÅFine motor development: A helped mix the batter and then transfer it over to the cupcake pan. Was it perfect? Nope. But, the focus that he had when he transferred the batter over was phenomenal. And of course putting the sprinkles - and even sneaking some into his belly! 

üßÅPatience: Have you ever tried to tell a toddler to wait? Has it ever worked?! Well, we had our moments too. We wanted to pour the batter before it was done combining, we wanted to eat the batter before it was done cooking, and well.. you get the point. But, I was able to talk A through it and have him practice some patience. It required a lot of prep and explaining, but he did so well! 

Overall, it was a fun activity. Have you tried baking with your littles? How was your experience? 
